Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm wide wedges
(no need to peel!). Pop the wedges on a large #baking tray{} in a single layer.
Drizzle with @oil{drizzle}, then season with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}.
Toss to coat, then spread out and roast on the top shelf of your oven until
golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

> Tip: Use two baking trays if necessary, you want the potatoes nicely spread out.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}. Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle}
in a large #frying pan{} over medium heat. Once hot, add the onion and season
with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch} and cook, stirring regularly, until soft
and caramelised, ~{8-10%minutes}. Add half the @balsamic vinegar{24%ml} with a
pinch of @sugar{pinch}(if you have some) and cook for ~{1%minute} until the
liquid has evaporated. Transfer to a small #bowl{} and set aside. Wipe out the
frying pan but don't wash it up!

Remove the stalk from the @portobello mushrooms{2} and discard the stalk (leave
the mushroom whole). Return the frying pan to medium high heat with a drizzle
of @oil{drizzle}. Add the mushroom to the pan and season with @salt{pinch} and
@pepper{pinch}, fry until golden brown, ~{3-4%minutes}, then turn over and cook
for a further ~{3-4%minutes}.

Once the potatoes are nearly done, move them to the middle of the oven.
Transfer the mushrooms (stalk side up) onto a #roasting tray{}. Divide the
@goat's cheese{62.5%g} between the mushrooms then bake on the top shelf of your
oven until the cheese has melted, ~{8-10%minutes}. Meanwhile, cut the
@ciabatta{2} in half (like a sandwich). Pop the ciabatta in the oven for the
last ~{3-4%minutes} to toast.

Meanwhile, pop the remaining @balsamic vinegar{} and a drizzle of @oil{drizzle}
into a bowl and season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Mix
together. Just before the mushroom goats cheese burger is ready, add the
@pea shoots{40%g} to the dressing, toss to coat.

Divide the ciabattas between plates and top the bottom half with the mushroom
then spoon over the balsamic onion. Top with some peashoots and the top of the
ciabatta. Serve with the wedges and remaining peashoots.